02:42.881 --> 02:45.576
[ Music ]

03:16.149 --> 03:18.250
[ Sighs ]

03:21.354 --> 03:23.556
Daniel Holden: Hello?

03:27.295 --> 03:31.298
Amantha: Oh, hello, Daniel.

03:31.300 --> 03:32.266
You awake?

03:32.268 --> 03:33.233
Uh-huh.

03:33.235 --> 03:38.639
Oh, um, I thought maybe we
could go to the refuge today.

03:38.641 --> 03:41.409
You remember the refuge?

03:41.411 --> 03:43.477
It's still there.

03:43.479 --> 03:46.013
They have a baboon now.

03:46.015 --> 03:47.882
A baboon.

03:47.884 --> 03:51.252
Yeah, it's just one.

03:51.254 --> 03:55.890
They have the usual suspects, too...
uh, bears, bisons,

03:55.892 --> 03:59.194
chickens, cockatiels,
cockatoos, cougars, cows.

03:59.196 --> 04:01.563
America versus the world.

04:01.565 --> 04:05.233
Deer, dogs, donkeys,
ducks, emus, geckos.

04:08.404 --> 04:11.072
Sound like fun?

04:11.074 --> 04:14.375
Oh, maybe later.

04:14.377 --> 04:16.177
I don't know yet.

04:17.413 --> 04:18.478
Oh, okay.

04:21.483 --> 04:23.752
Well, I'll just be downstairs.

04:23.754 --> 04:26.088
No worries.

04:26.090 --> 04:28.156
No worries.

04:37.167 --> 04:41.337
[ Music ]

05:15.272 --> 05:18.875
Three-hundred fifty
degrees, for 15 minutes.

05:18.877 --> 05:21.477
Good grief, mother.

05:21.479 --> 05:23.779
And thank you.

05:26.717 --> 05:30.153
Jared: I love this
country so much.

05:30.155 --> 05:33.456
If there's a bald eagle
right here, I'd bleep it.

05:33.458 --> 05:34.857
[ Laughing ]

05:34.859 --> 05:37.026
Claire: Oh, you-you're
getting a text.

05:40.965 --> 05:42.032
What-what is it?

05:42.034 --> 05:43.499
It-it's nothing.

05:43.501 --> 05:44.834
It's just my mom.

05:44.836 --> 05:47.103
Your mom?

05:47.105 --> 05:48.438
No, it's not.

05:48.440 --> 05:49.872
Claire, give it here.

05:49.874 --> 05:51.641
What is this?

05:51.643 --> 05:52.542
It-it's nothing.

05:52.544 --> 05:54.844
Just someone being annoying.

05:54.846 --> 05:57.814
"We're gonna kill your sis
and make you watch, bitch?"

05:57.816 --> 06:00.216
Could you give it back, please?

06:00.218 --> 06:01.484
Who sent this?

06:01.486 --> 06:03.886
Think I actually know?

06:03.888 --> 06:06.256
How long has this been going on?

06:06.258 --> 06:08.558
The last few days.

06:08.560 --> 06:11.227
Is this all of them?

06:11.229 --> 06:12.094
Jared?

06:12.096 --> 06:14.797
No.

06:14.799 --> 06:16.565
We have to tell somebody.

06:16.567 --> 06:17.700
Who?

06:17.702 --> 06:19.601
Usually moms are a good start.

06:19.603 --> 06:22.004
My mom, seriously.

06:22.006 --> 06:24.305
Well, we have to do something.

06:24.307 --> 06:28.876
- I mean, what if somebody
really means it-- - Okay, fine.

06:28.878 --> 06:31.179
Can I have my phone back please?

06:32.248 --> 06:34.349
You're gettin'
dessert this time.

06:34.351 --> 06:35.417
Jon Stern: Well, we'll see.

06:35.419 --> 06:36.918
I wasn't asking.

06:39.823 --> 06:43.259
Senator Roland Foulkes: Got
himself the wildcat special.

06:47.130 --> 06:48.563
How are the biscuits today?

06:50.800 --> 06:53.068
Good-- biscuits are good.

06:53.070 --> 06:56.738
That woman sure knows how to
make the dough rise, don't she?

07:00.376 --> 07:06.547
Listen, I just wanna say, uh, I think
it's a mighty noble thing you do.

07:06.549 --> 07:10.518
Trying to right wrongs,
defending innocent men.

07:10.520 --> 07:13.621
So, why don't you go
find yourself one?

07:13.623 --> 07:16.525
[ Chuckling ]

07:16.527 --> 07:19.294
Seriously, how's
the family doing?

07:19.296 --> 07:21.329
I'm a big fan of the Teds.

07:21.331 --> 07:27.635
Um... everyone's extremely happy to have
Daniel back home, where he belongs.

07:27.637 --> 07:29.703
I bet they are.

07:29.705 --> 07:33.807
And Daniel, how's he adjusting
to life on the outside?

07:33.809 --> 07:37.644
Daniel's extremely happy to be
back home where he belongs.

07:37.646 --> 07:40.314
I don't think that boy's ever been
extremely happy in his whole damn life.

07:40.316 --> 07:41.348
That's hard to say.

07:41.350 --> 07:44.419
He's never really had a life.

07:44.421 --> 07:46.588
You mind if we get real?

07:46.590 --> 07:49.357
I always try to keep
it real, senator.

07:49.359 --> 07:52.461
I don't give a rusty rat's
ass where the jizz landed.

07:52.463 --> 07:56.865
This case was airtight from the
moment we pried that poor dead girl

07:56.867 --> 07:58.433
from that boy's clammy hands.

07:58.435 --> 08:01.770
Not so much where it
landed, as whose it was.

08:01.772 --> 08:04.373
That thorny little issue's
gonna stick to you forever.

08:04.375 --> 08:09.412
Well, you got lucky with that panty
nonsense, I'll give you that.

08:09.414 --> 08:12.981
But I'm still not sure you
realize what you're doing.

08:12.983 --> 08:13.381
Is that right?

08:13.383 --> 08:17.752
Coming down here, givin' one family
false hope, and another a whole

08:17.754 --> 08:19.621
fresh set of grief.

08:19.623 --> 08:23.792
You ever consider how hard it's gonna be on
them when we drag his ass back to prison?

08:23.794 --> 08:25.761
He's going back to prison?

08:25.763 --> 08:26.695
See, that's news to me.

08:26.697 --> 08:29.899
I thought there would at least
be another trial first, ya know?

08:29.901 --> 08:33.602
Due process, that sort of thing.

08:33.604 --> 08:36.005
Well, it's not my call, is it?

08:36.006 --> 08:38.374
I'm just a humble state senator.

08:44.815 --> 08:50.453
That sister of his, she's a basket
of firecrackers, ain't she?

08:55.926 --> 08:58.394
It's always a pleasure, senator.

09:08.605 --> 09:11.207
Daniel, honey.

09:11.209 --> 09:12.374
Mom made a quiche.

09:12.376 --> 09:14.342
Can I come in?

09:14.344 --> 09:16.278
Better not.

09:19.349 --> 09:22.819
Well, it's-it's nice and warm.

09:24.585 --> 09:28.883
Could you just leave it outside?

09:28.885 --> 09:31.452
Outside the door?

09:31.454 --> 09:33.421
[ Exhales ]

09:35.990 --> 09:37.424
Uh-huh.

09:37.426 --> 09:39.626
Sure.

09:41.328 --> 09:43.548
[ Music ]

10:06.349 --> 10:08.951
Hey, Daniel.

10:08.953 --> 10:10.485
Everything all right?

10:16.192 --> 10:17.526
Daniel?

10:23.532 --> 10:25.199
Hey, Daniel, what's goin' on?

10:29.538 --> 10:31.739
My father died.

10:34.543 --> 10:35.809
What happened?

10:39.848 --> 10:43.084
Heart attack.

10:43.086 --> 10:45.487
I'm so sorry, man.

10:50.092 --> 10:52.160
Ted: Takin' off.

10:57.567 --> 10:59.801
Tawney: There's a piece
of monkey bread.

10:59.803 --> 11:02.003
What?

11:02.005 --> 11:04.840
On the counter, for your trip.

11:04.842 --> 11:05.941
That's sweet, honey.

11:05.943 --> 11:09.110
Thank you.

11:09.112 --> 11:12.747
Have fun.

11:12.749 --> 11:16.183
Won't be very much fun without
you there with me, sweetie.

11:16.185 --> 11:18.820
[ Whirring ]

11:30.867 --> 11:33.903
Are you vacuuming?

11:33.905 --> 11:35.772
What?

11:35.774 --> 11:38.575
Are you vacuuming?

11:38.577 --> 11:39.976
[ Turns off dust buster ]

11:39.978 --> 11:43.580
I-I'm almost done.

11:43.582 --> 11:46.950
You think you might be ready
to go out in a little bit?

11:49.854 --> 11:52.255
I don't know.

11:52.257 --> 11:55.592
I-I think I might
just lay low today.

11:55.594 --> 12:01.698
Oh, um... sure.

12:01.700 --> 12:03.433
I'm sorry.

12:03.435 --> 12:05.569
No, there's nothing
to be sorry about.

12:05.571 --> 12:10.942
But, I might go look at an
apartment really quick.

12:10.944 --> 12:13.477
Okay.

12:13.479 --> 12:16.614
'Cause I'm moving back here.

12:20.553 --> 12:25.690
Well, here's my cell
number, if you need me.

12:30.696 --> 12:35.166
[ Turns dust buster on ]

13:00.459 --> 13:04.195
Mr. Gaines, how are you doing?

13:04.197 --> 13:07.198
Rutherford Gaines:
Mr. Stern, welcome.

13:07.200 --> 13:10.034
Thank you, dear.

13:10.036 --> 13:14.940
I was sorry to hear about
your, uh, situation.

13:14.942 --> 13:18.343
How can I help ya?

13:18.345 --> 13:26.897
Well, um, any, uh, insights or regrets
you may have had about the case?

13:26.899 --> 13:29.300
[ Chuckling ]

13:29.302 --> 13:33.404
You're-you're a
fresh-faced boy, Mr. Stern.

13:33.406 --> 13:36.240
That's more a matter
of luck than talent.

13:36.242 --> 13:41.145
You keep at this and you'll have
two or three cases in your life

13:41.147 --> 13:42.813
make you look like me.

13:42.815 --> 13:46.484
Like Daniel's?

13:46.486 --> 13:49.054
How is he now?

13:49.056 --> 13:52.491
I don't know, sir.

13:52.493 --> 13:56.395
Boy was just a baby
when they put him in.

13:56.397 --> 13:58.531
Eighteen.

13:58.533 --> 14:03.970
What people never understand...
what-what gets lost

14:03.972 --> 14:12.013
in all this revisitin'... is the
tenor of the town back then.

14:12.015 --> 14:15.216
- I can only imagine.
- No, you can't, Mr. Stern.

14:15.218 --> 14:17.218
Not unless you bore
witness to it.

14:17.220 --> 14:20.088
Unless you was knee deep in it.

14:20.090 --> 14:21.423
Smelled it.

14:21.425 --> 14:22.924
Smelled what, sir?

14:22.926 --> 14:25.328
Some of your people know.

14:25.330 --> 14:27.430
The older ones.

14:27.432 --> 14:31.267
Humans don't change
that much in 50 years.

14:31.269 --> 14:33.803
Or 100, or 1,000.

14:33.805 --> 14:35.772
It's the laws that change.

14:35.774 --> 14:36.873
The rules of civilization.

14:40.177 --> 14:44.047
We just repeat ourselves.

14:44.049 --> 14:46.249
Everybody with a part to play.

14:48.286 --> 14:51.522
What part did Daniel play, sir?

14:51.524 --> 14:54.491
Hannah was a girl of no means.

14:54.493 --> 14:57.194
Beautiful.

14:57.196 --> 14:59.363
Whip smart.

14:59.365 --> 15:00.931
Damned honor student.

15:00.933 --> 15:05.069
Daniel was a-a strange boy.

15:08.540 --> 15:10.842
Last I checked,
that's not a crime.

15:10.844 --> 15:16.080
My best hope was keep
the boy off death row.

15:16.082 --> 15:20.017
Wanted to enter a guilty
plea, but Daniel's father

15:20.019 --> 15:22.586
wasn't having none of it.

15:22.588 --> 15:26.389
I need his file sir.

15:26.391 --> 15:28.057
All gone, son.

15:28.059 --> 15:28.958
What?

15:28.960 --> 15:31.694
My daughter, she
threw 'em all away.

15:31.696 --> 15:32.595
Why would she do that?

15:32.597 --> 15:34.863
Well, she was so mad, she
couldn't help herself.

15:34.865 --> 15:36.999
People don't want that
stuff laying around.

15:37.001 --> 15:39.134
Boxes and boxes of pain.

15:39.136 --> 15:40.869
It's human nature.

15:40.871 --> 15:44.873
They wan-wanna get past it.

15:44.875 --> 15:47.809
I don't know why she chose
to stay in this town.

15:47.811 --> 15:49.244
The grief she took.

15:49.246 --> 15:52.147
Her, just a lawyer's
daughter, and, of course,

15:52.149 --> 15:53.549
she had her part to play, too.

15:53.551 --> 15:54.917
Don't ya see?

15:54.919 --> 15:58.521
Coming home from teachin'
school, crying and carrying on.

15:58.523 --> 16:00.890
Begging me to quit the case.

16:00.892 --> 16:01.857
Course I couldn't.

16:01.859 --> 16:04.927
Had to play my part,
too, to the bitter end.

16:04.929 --> 16:06.161
Mr. Gaines, please.

16:06.163 --> 16:10.833
- I could tell you...
- Tell me what?

16:13.303 --> 16:18.474
I'm not so sure we didn't
come from goddamn monkeys.

16:18.476 --> 16:20.843
Going to nowhere.

16:22.212 --> 16:26.648
Sorry-- wish I could help ya.

16:26.650 --> 16:31.620
Just don't let all this
technology lull ya, son.

16:31.622 --> 16:32.287
How's that?

16:32.289 --> 16:36.932
If you're thinking we're
in modern times...

16:39.877 --> 16:42.230
watch yourself.

17:01.144 --> 17:03.078
Hello?

17:15.257 --> 17:17.969
[ Music ]

18:00.270 --> 18:02.983
[ Music ]

18:20.758 --> 18:23.126
[ Rap music ]

18:53.724 --> 18:56.614
[ Music ]

